# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abolitionism-animal-rights
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The first country to fully outlaw slavery was France in 1315, though it was later used in its colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The first country to abolish and punish slavery for indigenous people was Spain with the New Laws in 1542.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Under the actions of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, chattel slavery was abolished across Japan since 1590, though other forms of forced labor were used during World War II.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The first and only country to self-liberate from slavery was a former French colony, Haiti, as a result of the Revolution of 1791–1804.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The British abolitionist movement began in the late 18th century, and the 1772 Somersett case established that slavery did not exist in English law.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1807, the slave trade was made illegal throughout the British Empire, though existing slaves in British colonies were not liberated until the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the United States, Pennsylvania and Vermont were the first states to abolish slavery, Vermont in 1777 and Pennsylvania in 1780 (Vermont did not join the Union until 1791).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] By 1804, the rest of the northern states had abolished slavery, but it remained legal in southern states.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] By 1808, the United States outlawed the importation of slaves and in 1865 outlawed slavery except as a punishment.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In Eastern Europe, groups organized to abolish the enslavement of the Roma in Wallachia and Moldavia between 1843 and 1855, and to emancipate the serfs in Russia in 1861.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The United States would pass the 13th Amendment in December 1865 after having just fought a bloody Civil War, ending slavery "except as a punishment for crime".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1888, Brazil became the last country in the Americas to outlaw slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As the Empire of Japan annexed Asian countries, from the late 19th century onwards, archaic institutions including slavery were abolished in those countries.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1948, slavery was declared illegal in the United Nations' Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] By this time, the Arab world was the only region in the world where institutional chattel slavery was still legal.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Slavery in Saudi Arabia, slavery in Yemen and slavery in Dubai were abolished in 1962–1963, with slavery in Oman following in 1970.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Mauritania is the latest country to officially abolish slavery, with a presidential decree in 1981.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Today, child and adult slavery and forced labor are illegal in almost all countries, as well as being against international law, but human trafficking for labor and for sexual slavery continues to affect tens of millions of adults and children.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Balthild of Chelles, herself a former slave, queen consort of Neustria and Burgundy by marriage to Clovis II, became regent in 657 since the king, her son Chlothar III, was only five years old.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] At some unknown date during her rule, she abolished the trade of slaves, although not slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Moreover, her (and contemporaneous Saint Eligius') favorite charity was to buy and free slaves, especially children.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Slavery started to dwindle and would be superseded by serfdom.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1315, Louis X, king of France, published a decree proclaiming that "France signifies freedom" and that any slave setting foot on French soil should be freed.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] This prompted subsequent governments to circumscribe slavery in the overseas colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Some cases of African slaves freed by setting foot on French soil were recorded such as the example of a Norman slave merchant who tried to sell slaves in Bordeaux in 1571.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] He was arrested and his slaves were freed according to a declaration of the Parlement of Guyenne which stated that slavery was intolerable in France, although it is a misconception that there were 'no slaves in France'; thousands of African slaves were present in France during the 18th century.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Born into slavery in Saint Domingue, Thomas-Alexandre Dumas became free when his father brought him to France in 1776.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As in other New World colonies, the French relied on the Atlantic slave trade for labor for their sugar cane plantations in their Caribbean colonies; the French West Indies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In addition, French colonists in *Louisiane* in North America held slaves, particularly in the South around New Orleans, where they established sugarcane plantations.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Louis XIV's *Code Noir* regulated the slave trade and institution in the colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It included the right to marry, gather publicly or take Sundays off.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Although the *Code Noir* authorized and codified cruel corporal punishment against slaves under certain conditions, it forbade slave owners to torture them or to separate families.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It also demanded enslaved Africans receive instruction in the Catholic faith, implying that Africans were human beings endowed with a soul, a fact French law did not admit until then.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It resulted in a far higher percentage of Black people being free in 1830 (13.2% in Louisiana compared to 0.8% in Mississippi).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] They were on average exceptionally literate, with a significant number of them owning businesses, properties, and even slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Other free people of colour, such as Julien Raimond, spoke out against slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The *Code Noir* also forbade interracial marriages, but it was often ignored in French colonial society and the mulattoes became an intermediate caste between whites and blacks, while in the British colonies mulattoes and blacks were considered equal and discriminated against equally.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] During the Age of Enlightenment, many philosophers wrote pamphlets against slavery and its moral and economical justifications, including Montesquieu in *The Spirit of the Laws* (1748) and Denis Diderot in the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, Jacques Pierre Brissot founded the Society of the Friends of the Blacks (*Société des Amis des Noirs*) to work for the abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] After the Revolution, on 4 April 1792, France granted free people of colour full citizenship.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The slave revolt, in the largest Caribbean French colony of Saint-Domingue in 1791, was the beginning of what became the Haitian Revolution led by formerly enslaved people like Georges Biassou, Toussaint L'Ouverture, and Jean-Jacques Dessalines.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion swept through the north of the colony, and with it came freedom to thousands of enslaved blacks, but also violence and death.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1793, French Civil Commissioners in St.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Domingue and abolitionists, Léger-Félicité Sonthonax and Étienne Polverel, issued the first emancipation proclamation of the modern world (Decree of 16 Pluviôse An II).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Convention sent them to safeguard the allegiance of the population to revolutionary France.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The proclamation resulted in crucial military strategy as it gradually brought most of the black troops into the French fold and kept the colony under the French flag for most of the conflict.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The connection with France lasted until blacks and free people of colour formed L'armée indigène in 1802 to resist Napoleon's Expédition de Saint-Domingue.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Victory over the French in the decisive Battle of Vertières finally led to independence and the creation of present Haiti in 1804.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The convention, the first elected Assembly of the First Republic (1792–1804), on 4 February 1794, under the leadership of Maximilien Robespierre, abolished slavery in law in France and its colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Abbé Grégoire and the Society of the Friends of the Blacks were part of the abolitionist movement, which had laid important groundwork in building anti-slavery sentiment in the metropole.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The first article of the law stated that "Slavery was abolished" in the French colonies, while the second article stated that "slave-owners would be indemnified" with financial compensation for the value of their slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The French constitution passed in 1795 included in the declaration of the Rights of Man that slavery was abolished.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars, French slave-owners joined the counter-revolution en masse and, through the Whitehall Accord, they threatened to move the French Caribbean colonies to British control, as Great Britain still allowed slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Fearing secession from these islands, successfully lobbied by planters and concerned about revenues from the West Indies, and influenced by the slaveholder family of his wife, Napoleon Bonaparte decided to re-establish slavery after becoming First Consul.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] He promulgated the law of 20 May 1802 and sent military governors and troops to the colonies to impose it.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] On 10 May 1802, Colonel Delgrès launched a rebellion in Guadeloupe against Napoleon's representative, General Richepanse.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion was repressed, and slavery was re-established.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The news of the Law of 4 February 1794 that abolished slavery in France and its colonies and the revolution led by Colonel Delgrès sparked another wave of rebellion in Saint-Domingue.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] From 1802 Napoleon sent more than 20,000 troops to the island, two-thirds died, mostly from yellow fever.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Seeing the failure of the Saint-Domingue expedition, in 1803 Napoleon decided to sell the Louisiana Territory to the United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The French governments initially refused to recognize Haïti.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It forced the nation to pay a substantial amount of reparations (which it could ill afford) for losses during the revolution and did not recognize its government until 1825.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] France was a signatory to the first multilateral treaty for the suppression of the slave trade, the Treaty for the Suppression of the African Slave Trade (1841), but the king, Louis Philippe I, declined to ratify it.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] On 27 April 1848, under the Second Republic (1848–1852), the decree-law written by Victor Schœlcher abolished slavery in the remaining colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The state bought the slaves from the *colons* (white colonists; *Békés* in Creole), and then freed them.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] At about the same time, France started colonizing Africa and had gained possession of much of West Africa by 1900.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1905, the French abolished slavery in most of French West Africa.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The French also attempted to abolish Tuareg slavery following the Kaocen Revolt.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the region of the Sahel, slavery has long persisted.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The abolition wasn't strictly put in place.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Several french territories kept practising slavery until 1904 as was the case in Senegal or 1894 in Soudan.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The abolition was not strictly enforced.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Passed on 10 May 2001, the Taubira law officially acknowledges slavery and the Atlantic slave trade as a crime against humanity.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] 10 May was chosen as the day dedicated to recognition of the crime of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Soon after Oglethorpe's death in 1785, Sharp and More united with William Wilberforce and others in forming the Clapham Sect.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Somersett case in 1772, in which a fugitive slave was freed with the judgement that slavery did not exist under English common law, helped launch the British movement to abolish slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Though anti-slavery sentiments were widespread by the late 18th century, many colonies and emerging nations continued to use slave labor: Dutch, French, British, Spanish, and Portuguese territories in the West Indies, South America, and the Southern United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] After the American Revolution established the United States, many Loyalists who fled the Northern United States immigrated to the British province of Quebec, bringing an English majority population as well as many slaves, leading the province to ban the institution in 1793 (see Slavery in Canada).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1787, the Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade was formed in London.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The last known form of enforced servitude of adults (villeinage) had disappeared in England by the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1569 a court considered the case of Cartwright, who had bought a slave from Russia.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The court ruled English law could not recognize slavery, as it was never established officially.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] This ruling was overshadowed by later developments; it was upheld in 1700 by the Lord Chief Justice John Holt when he ruled that a slave became free as soon as he arrived in England.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] During the English Civil Wars of the mid-seventeenth century, sectarian radicals challenged slavery and other threats to personal freedom.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Their ideas influenced many antislavery thinkers in the eighteenth century.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In addition to English colonists importing slaves to the North American colonies, by the 18th century, traders began to import slaves from Africa, India and East Asia (where they were trading) to London and Edinburgh to work as personal servants.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Men who migrated to the North American colonies often took their East Indian slaves or servants with them, as East Indians have been documented in colonial records.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Some of the first freedom suits, court cases in the British Isles to challenge the legality of slavery, took place in Scotland in 1755 and 1769.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Each of the slaves had been baptized in Scotland and challenged the legality of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] They set the precedent of legal procedure in British courts that would later lead to successful outcomes for the plaintiffs.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In these cases, deaths of the plaintiff and defendant, respectively, brought an end before court decisions.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] African slaves were not bought or sold in London but were brought by masters from other areas.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Together with people from other nations, especially non-Christian, Africans were considered foreigners, not able to be English subjects.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] At the time, England had no naturalization procedure.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The African slaves' legal status was unclear until 1772 and Somersett's Case, when the fugitive slave James Somersett forced a decision by the courts.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Somersett had escaped, and his master, Charles Steuart, had him captured and imprisoned on board a ship, intending to ship him to Jamaica to be resold into slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] While in London, Somersett had been baptized; three godparents issued a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As a result, Lord Mansfield, Chief Justice of the Court of the King's Bench, had to judge whether Somersett's abduction was lawful or not under English common law.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] No legislation had ever been passed to establish slavery in England.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The case received national attention, and five advocates supported the action on behalf of Somersett.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Although the exact legal implications of the judgement are unclear when analysed by lawyers, the judgement was generally taken at the time to have determined that slavery did not exist under English common law and was thus prohibited in England.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The decision did not apply to the British overseas territories; by then, for example, the American colonies had established slavery by positive laws.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Somersett's case became a significant part of the common law of slavery in the English-speaking world and it helped launch the movement to abolish slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] After reading about Somersett's Case, Joseph Knight, an enslaved African who had been purchased by his master John Wedderburn in Jamaica and brought to Scotland, left him.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Married and with a child, he filed a freedom suit, on the grounds that he could not be held as a slave in Great Britain.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* (1778), Wedderburn said that Knight owed him "perpetual servitude".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Court of Session of Scotland ruled against him, saying that chattel slavery was not recognized under the law of Scotland, and slaves could seek court protection to leave a master or avoid being forcibly removed from Scotland to be returned to slavery in the colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] But at the same time, legally mandated, hereditary slavery of Scots persons in Scotland had existed from 1606 and continued until 1799, when colliers and salters were emancipated by an act of the Parliament of Great Britain (39 Geo.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Skilled workers, they were restricted to a place and could be sold with the works.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] 28) was intended to end what the act referred to as "a state of slavery and bondage", but that was ineffective, necessitating the 1799 act.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the 1776 book *The Wealth of Nations*, Adam Smith argued for the abolition of slavery on economic grounds.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Smith pointed out that slavery incurred security, housing, and food costs that the use of free labor would not, and opined that free workers would be more productive because they would have personal economic incentives to work harder.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The death rate (and thus repurchase cost) of slaves was also high, and people are less productive when not allowed to choose the type of work they prefer, are illiterate, and are forced to live and work in miserable and unhealthy conditions.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The free labor markets and international free trade that Smith preferred would also result in different prices and allocations that Smith believed would be more efficient and productive for consumers.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Prior to the American Revolution, there were few significant initiatives in the American colonies that led to the abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Kent was the lawyer who took on most of the cases of slaves suing their masters for personal illegal enslavement.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] He was the first lawyer to successfully establish a slave's freedom.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In addition, Brigadier General Samuel Birch created the *Book of Negroes*, to establish which slaves were free after the war.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1783, an anti-slavery movement began among the British public to end slavery throughout the British Empire.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] After the formation of the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade in 1787, William Wilberforce led the cause of abolition through the parliamentary campaign.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson became the group's most prominent researcher, gathering vast amounts of data on the trade.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] One aspect of abolitionism during this period was the effective use of images such as the famous Josiah Wedgwood "Am I Not A Man and a Brother?" anti-slavery medallion of 1787.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Clarkson described the medallion as "promoting the cause of justice, humanity and freedom".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The 1792 Slave Trade Bill passed the House of Commons mangled and mutilated by the modifications and amendments of Pitt, it lay for years, in the House of Lords.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Biographer William Hague considers the unfinished abolition of the slave trade to be Pitt's greatest failure.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 was passed by the British Parliament on 25 March 1807, making the slave trade illegal throughout the British Empire.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Britain used its influence to coerce other countries to agree to treaties to end their slave trade and allow the Royal Navy to seize their slave ships.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Britain enforced the abolition of the trade because the act made trading slaves within British territories illegal.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] However, the act repealed the Amelioration Act 1798 which attempted to improve conditions for slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The end of the slave trade did not end slavery as a whole.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the 1820s, the abolitionist movement revived to campaign against the institution of slavery itself.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1823 the first Anti-Slavery Society, the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions, was founded.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Many of its members had previously campaigned against the slave trade.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] On 28 August 1833, the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 was passed.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It purchased the slaves from their masters and paved the way for the abolition of slavery throughout the British Empire by 1838, after which the first Anti-Slavery Society was wound up.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1839, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society was formed by Joseph Sturge, which attempted to outlaw slavery worldwide and also to pressure the government to help enforce the suppression of the slave trade by declaring slave traders to be pirates.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The world's oldest international human rights organization, it continues today as Anti-Slavery International.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson was the key speaker at the World Anti-Slavery Convention it held in London in 1840.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the principalities of Wallachia and Moldavia, the government held slavery of the Roma (often referred to as Gypsies) as legal at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The progressive pro-European and anti-Ottoman movement, which gradually gained power in the two principalities, also worked to abolish that slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Between 1843 and 1855, the principalities emancipated all of the 250,000 enslaved Roma people.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Bartolomé de las Casas was a 16th-century Spanish Dominican priest, the first resident Bishop of Chiapas (Central America, today Mexico).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As a settler in the New World he witnessed and opposed the poor treatment and virtual slavery of the Native Americans by the Spanish colonists, under the encomienda system.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] He advocated before King Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor on behalf of rights for the natives.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Las Casas for 20 years worked to get African slaves imported to replace natives; African slavery was everywhere and no one talked of ridding the New World of it, though France had abolished slavery in France itself and there was talk in other countries about doing the same.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] However, Las Casas had a late change of heart, and became an advocate for the Africans in the colonies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] His book, *A Short Account of the Destruction of the Indies*, contributed to Spanish passage of colonial legislation known as the New Laws of 1542, which abolished native slavery for the first time in European colonial history.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It ultimately led to the Valladolid debate, the first European debate about the rights of colonized people.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] During the early 19th century, slavery expanded rapidly in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States, while at the same time the new republics of mainland Spanish America became committed to the gradual abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] During the Spanish American wars for independence (1810–1826), slavery was abolished in most of Latin America, though it continued until 1873 in Puerto Rico, 1886 in Cuba, and 1888 in Brazil (where it was abolished by the *Lei Áurea*, the "Golden Law").
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Chile declared freedom of wombs in 1811, followed by the United Provinces of the River Plate in 1813, Colombia and Venezuela in 1821, but without abolishing slavery completely.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] While Chile abolished slavery in 1823, Argentina did so with the signing of the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Slavery was abolished in Uruguay during the *Guerra Grande*, by both the government of Fructuoso Rivera and the government in exile of Manuel Oribe.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Throughout the growth of slavery in the American South, Nova Scotia became a destination for black refugees leaving Southern Colonies and United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] While many blacks who arrived in Nova Scotia during the American Revolution were free, others were not.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Black slaves also arrived in Nova Scotia as the property of White American Loyalists.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1772, prior to the American Revolution, Britain determined that slavery could not exist in the British Isles followed by the *Knight v.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* decision in Scotland in 1778.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] This decision, in turn, influenced the colony of Nova Scotia.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, abolitionist James Drummond MacGregor from Pictou published the first anti-slavery literature in Canada and began purchasing slaves' freedom and chastising his colleagues in the Presbyterian church who owned slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Led by Richard John Uniacke, in 1787, 1789 and again on 11 January 1808, the Nova Scotian legislature refused to legalize slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Two chief justices, Thomas Andrew Lumisden Strange (1790–1796) and Sampson Salter Blowers (1797–1832) were instrumental in freeing slaves from their owners in Nova Scotia.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] They were held in high regard in the colony.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] By the end of the War of 1812 and the arrival of the Black Refugees, there were few slaves left in Nova Scotia.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 outlawed the slave trade in the British Empire and the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 outlawed slavery altogether.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] With slaves escaping to New York and New England, legislation for gradual emancipation was passed in Upper Canada (1793) and Lower Canada (1803).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In Upper Canada, the Act Against Slavery of 1793 was passed by the Assembly under the auspices of John Graves Simcoe.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It was the first legislation against slavery in the British Empire.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Under its provisions no new slaves could be imported, slaves already in the province would remain enslaved until death, and children born to female slaves would be slaves but must be freed at the age of 25.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The last slaves in Canada gained their freedom when slavery was abolished in the entire British Empire by the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In his book *The Struggle For Equality*, historian James M.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] McPherson defines an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional, and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] He does not include antislavery activists such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party, which called for the gradual ending of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Franklin, a slaveholder for much of his life, became a leading member of the Pennsylvania Society for the Abolition of Slavery, the first recognized organization for abolitionists in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, Northern states abolished slavery, beginning with the 1777 Constitution of Vermont, followed by Pennsylvania's gradual emancipation act in 1780.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Other states with more of an economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, also passed gradual emancipation laws, and by 1804, all the Northern states had abolished it, although this did not mean that already enslaved people were freed.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Some had to work without wages as "indentured servants" for two more decades, although they could no longer be sold.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The 1836–1837 campaign to end free speech in Alton, Illinois, culminated in the 7 November 1837 mob murder of abolitionist newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy, which was covered in newspapers nationwide, causing a rise in membership in abolitionist societies.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] By 1840 more than 15,000 people were members of abolitionist societies in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the 1850s in the fifteen states constituting the American South, slavery was legally established.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] While it was fading away in the cities as well as in the border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cotton for export, or sugar, tobacco, or hemp.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] According to the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] American abolitionism was based in the North, although there were anti-abolitionist riots in several cities.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the South abolitionism was illegal, and abolitionist publications, like The Liberator, could not be sent to Southern post offices.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Amos Dresser, a white alumnus of Lane Theological Seminary, was publicly whipped in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing abolitionist publications.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In addition, laws were passed to further repress slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] These laws included anti-literacy laws and anti-gathering laws.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The anti-gathering laws were applied to religious gatherings of free blacks and slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] These laws, passed around the 1820–1850 period, were blamed in the South on Northern abolitionists.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As one slaveowner wrote, "I can tell you.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Abolitionism in the United States became a popular expression of moralism, operating in tandem with other social reform efforts, such as the temperance movement, and much more problematically, the women's suffrage movement.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison (founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society) and writers Wendell Phillips, John Greenleaf Whittier, and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners of using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Republican Party wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because it believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] White Southern leaders said that the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the territories made them second-class citizens and, as the *Dred Scott* decision held, infringed slaveholders' property rights.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and the labor of enslaved people decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the Confederacy's firing on Fort Sumter, a Union fort in South Carolina.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, four slave states, known as the border states (Maryland, Missouri, Delaware, and Kentucky), chose to remain in the Union.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] On 16 April 1862, Abraham Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, abolishing slavery in Washington D.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of escaped slaves from the South rushing to Union lines.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, called contrabands, so that they would not be returned to their masters in the Confederacy.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] On 1 January 1863, Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which was an executive order of the U.S. government that changed the legal status of 3 million slaves in the Confederacy from "slave" to "henceforward ... free".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Though slaves were legally freed by the Proclamation, they became actually free by escaping to federal lines, or by advances of federal troops.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Even before the Emancipation Proclamation, many former slaves served the federal army as teamsters, cooks, laundresses, and laborers, as well as scouts, spies, and guides.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Plantation owners sometimes moved the Black people they claimed to own as far as possible out of reach of the Union army.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] By "Juneteenth" (19 June 1865, in Texas), the Union Army controlled all of the Confederacy and liberated all its slaves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The owners were never compensated; nor were freed slaves compensated by former owners.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The border states were exempt from the Emancipation Proclamation, but they too (except Delaware) began their own emancipation programs.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As the war dragged on, both the federal government and Union states continued to take measures against slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In June 1864, the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, which required free states to aid in returning escaped slaves to slave states, was repealed.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The state of Maryland abolished slavery on 13 October 1864.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Missouri abolished slavery on 11 January 1865.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] West Virginia, which had been admitted to the Union in 1863 as a slave state, but on the condition of gradual emancipation, fully abolished slavery on 3 February 1865.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Constitution took effect in December 1865, seven months after the end of the war, and finally ended slavery for non-criminals throughout the United States.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It also abolished slavery among the Indian tribes, including the Alaska tribes that became part of the U.S. in 1867.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Brazil and Cuba abolished slavery in the 1880s, with Cuba ending it in 1886 and Brazil in 1888.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] While actors like Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda in Cuba and Adelina Charuteira in Brazil worked to end slavery, it was enslaved people themselves who worked daily to chip away at enslavers' local authority.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] These practices are regionally specific based on the legal customs of the region that enslaved people knew well from centuries of interactions with Iberian slave laws.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] A key avenue for these legal arguments was the prominence of "lo extrajudicial", a field of legal interactions adjacent to a lawsuit explained by historian Bianca Premo as consisting of out-of-court settlements, public revelations, and face-to-face encounters.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The suffering of women in slavery was a common trope consistently used in abolitionists' rhetoric on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] This was especially true as it relates to the image of suffering mothers and their children.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Towards the end of the nineteenth century as slavery was coming to an end throughout the Atlantic world, images appearing in abolitionist publications routinely included images of families being torn apart and pregnant women being forced to do hard labor.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As countries imposed "free womb laws" to soften the image of slavery and bring about gradual emancipation, for many it raised the question of the justice of women being used to carry out emancipation without benefiting from it themselves.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Speeches given on the topic at the time focused on mothers and compared them to "all other mothers", using motherhood to level the subjects and objects of their speech.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Women were also often on the forefront of the abolition movement.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Authors such as Harriet Beecher Stowe (United States) and Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda (Brazil) used their novels to call into question the humanity of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Women such as the Grimké Sisters, Abigail Adams, Elizabeth Cady Stanton and others used their connections to political movements to advocate for the abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women such as Phillis Wheatley and Harriet Tubman took matters into their own hands by challenging the institution of slavery through their writing and their actions.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women like Adelina Charuteira used their mobility as street vendors and as much access as they had to literacy to spread information about abolition between freedom-seeking people and local abolitionist networks.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] White and black opponents of slavery, who played a considerable role in the movement.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] This list includes some escaped slaves, who were traditionally called abolitionists.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The first international attempt to address the abolition of slavery was the World Anti-Slavery Convention, organised by the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society at Exeter Hall in London, on 12–23 June 1840.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] This was however an attempt made by NGOs, not by state and governments.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In the late 19th century, the issue was addressed on an international level by states and governments.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Brussels Anti-Slavery Conference 1889–90 addressed slavery on a semi-global level via the representatives of the colonial powers.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] It had concluded with the Brussels Conference Act of 1890.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The 1890 Act was revised by the Convention of Saint-Germain-en-Laye 1919.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] During the 20th century the issue of slavery was addressed by the League of Nations, which founded commissions to investigate and eradicate the institution of slavery and slave trade worldwide.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The Temporary Slavery Commission (TSC), which was founded in 1924, conducted a global investigation and filed a report, and a convention was drawn up to hasten the total abolition of slavery and the slave trade.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The 1926 Slavery Convention, which was founded upon the investigation of the TSC of the League of Nations, was a turning point in banning global slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In 1932, the League formed the Committee of Experts on Slavery (CES) to review the result and enforcement of the 1926 Slavery Convention, which resulted in a new international investigation under the first permanent slavery committee, the Advisory Committee of Experts on Slavery (ACE).
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The ACE conducted a major international investigation on slavery and slave trade, inspecting all the colonial empires and the territories under their control between 1934 and 1939.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted in 1948 by the UN General Assembly, explicitly banned slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] After World War II, chattel slavery was formally abolished by law in almost the entire world, with the exception of the Arabian Peninsula and some parts of Africa.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Chattel slavery was still legal in Saudi Arabia, in Yemen, in the Trucial States and in Oman, and slaves were supplied to the Arabian Peninsula via the Red Sea slave trade.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The United Nations 1956 Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery was convened to outlaw and ban slavery worldwide, including child slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In November 1962, Faisal of Saudi Arabia finally prohibited the owning of slaves in Saudi Arabia, followed by the abolition of slavery in Yemen in 1962, slavery in Dubai 1963 and slavery in Oman in 1970.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In December 1966, the UN General Assembly adopted the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which was developed from the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of this international treaty bans slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The treaty came into force in March 1976 after it had been ratified by 35 nations.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] As of November 2003, 104 nations had ratified the treaty.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] However, illegal forced labor involves millions of people in the 21st century, 43% for sexual exploitation and 32% for economic exploitation.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Currently, the Anti-trafficking Coordination Team Initiative (ACT Team Initiative), a coordinated effort between the U.S.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Departments of Justice, Homeland Security, and Labor, addresses human trafficking.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] The International Labour Organization estimates that there are 20.9 million victims of human trafficking globally, including 5.5 million children, of which 55% are women and girls.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] In societies with large proportions of the population working in conditions of slavery or serfdom, stroke-of-the-pen laws declaring abolition can have thorough-going social, economic and political consequences.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p01] Issues of compensation/redemption, land-redistribution and citizenship can prove intractable.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] People in modern times have commemorated abolitionist movements and the abolition of slavery in different ways around the world.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] The United Nations General Assembly declared 2004 the International Year to Commemorate the Struggle against Slavery and its Abolition.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] This proclamation marked the bicentenary of the proclamation of the first modern slavery-free state, Haiti.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Numerous exhibitions, events and research programmes became associated with the initiative.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] 2007 witnessed major exhibitions in British museums and galleries to mark the anniversary of the 1807 abolition act – 1807 Commemorated 2008 marked the 201st anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade in the British Empire.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] It also marked the 175th anniversary of the abolition of slavery in the British Empire.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] The Faculty of Law at the University of Ottawa held a major international conference entitled, "Routes to Freedom: Reflections on the Bicentenary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade", from 14 to 16 March 2008.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Abolitionist constitutionalism is a line of thinking which invokes the historical view of the Constitution of the United States as an abolitionist document.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] It calls for an appeal to constitutionalism and progressive constitutionalism.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] This vision is interdisciplinary and finds its roots in the anti-slavery movement in the United States of America and is largely based on the tenet that current state institutions, particularly the carceral system, is rooted in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Some constitutional abolitionists critique the claim that the Constitution was pro-slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionist constitutionalism calls for the idea of dignity and the use of jurisprudence to address social inequalities.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Constitution was pro-slavery, the Reconstruction Amendments can be seen as a compromise for freedom, without allowing for the full abolition.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Criminal punishment was a major way that Southern states maintained the exploitation of black labor and effectively nullified the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] This was done namely through Black Codes, harsh vagrancy laws, apprenticeship laws and extreme punishment for black people.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] The Reconstruction Amendments in their aim to promote citizenship and emancipation are believed by these thinkers to still be guiding principles in the fight for freedom and abolition.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] There are suggestions that a broad reading of the Thirteenth Amendment can convey an abolitionist vision of the freedom advocated for by black people in the public sphere beyond emancipation.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Section one of the Fourteenth Amendment was used by many abolitionist lawyers and activists throughout the North to advance the case against slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Proponents of abolitionist constitutionalism believe the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments can be used today to extend the abolitionist logics to the various current barriers to injustices that are faced by marginalized peoples.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Just like abolitionism more generally, abolitionist constitutionalism seeks to provide a vision which will lead to the abolition of many different neoliberal state institutions, such as the prison industrial complex, the wage system, and policing.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] This is tied to a belief that white supremacy is woven into the fabric of legal state institutions.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionists are often marginalized.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] There is a belief that constitutionalism as a main tenet of radical abolitionism can change and appeal to the popular opinion more.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Historically, slavery abolitionists have had to use the public meaning of Constitutional terms in order in their fight against slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Constitutional abolitionists are generally in favour of incremental changes that follow the principles of the Reconstructive Amendments.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Some argue that the narrative and scholarly literature around Reconstruction Amendments is not coherent regarding their original aims.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] On 10 December 1948, the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Although outlawed in most countries, slavery is nonetheless practised secretly in many parts of the world.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Enslavement still takes place in the United States, Europe, and Latin America, as well as parts of Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Modern slavery keeps around 50 million people from exercising their freedom.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] In Mauritania alone, estimates are that up to 600,000 men, women and children, or 20% of the population, are enslaved.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Modern-day abolitionists have emerged over the last several years, as awareness of slavery around the world has grown, with groups such as Anti-Slavery International, the American Anti-Slavery Group, International Justice Mission, and Free the Slaves working to rid the world of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] In the United States, The Action Group to End Human Trafficking and Modern-Day Slavery is a coalition of NGOs, foundations and corporations working to develop a policy agenda for abolishing slavery and human trafficking.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Since 1997, the United States Department of Justice has, through work with the Coalition of Immokalee Workers, prosecuted six individuals in Florida on charges of slavery in the agricultural industry.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] These prosecutions have led to freedom for over 1000 enslaved workers in the tomato and orange fields of South Florida.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] This is only one example of the contemporary fight against slavery worldwide.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Slavery exists most widely in agricultural labor, apparel and sex industries, and service jobs in some regions.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] In 2000, the United States passed the Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act (TVPA) "to combat trafficking in persons, especially into the sex trade, slavery, and involuntary servitude".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] The 13th amendment abolished slavery in the United States "except as a punishment for crime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted".
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] In 2018, Colorado became the first state to remove similar language in its state constitution by a legislatively referred ballot referendum.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/abolitionism-p02] Other states have followed suit, but implementation has relied on court rulings.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was the son of a surgeon and was born at Waiblingen in 1677.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] He studied theology at Württemberg but also took interest in anatomy and natural science.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen became a pastor and advocate of pietism in Leonberg.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was influenced by the writings of Philipp Spener.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen argued for a compassionate treatment of the animals from a Christian theological framework.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] In 1711, Weigen authored *De Jure Hominis in Creaturas*.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] It has been described as "the first work ever to deal with the topic of animal rights as a general theme." The book became known in Denmark and inspired Laurids Smith.
[src:abolitionism-animal-rights/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen moved to Wahlheim, where he died in 1727.
